PSL190H1-S-20219.courseTitle: Biomedical Research at the Cutting Edge
PSL190H1-S-20219.courseDescription: Explore the thought processes, logic, motivation, techniques, analysis and impact of recent high-profile publications to gain insight into the enterprise of science. Outstanding scientists present recent high-impact papers, and students will examine the research in depth, focusing on the underlying questions, experimental approach, results and significance. Restricted to first-year students. Not available for CR/NCR option.
PSL190H1-S-20219.prerequisite: SBI4U and SCH4U (Grade 12 University Preparation Biology and Chemistry); permission of Department

PSL201Y1-Y-20219.courseDescription: A survey course covering all organ systems intended for students who are not proceeding further in Physiology.
PSL201Y1-Y-20219.exclusion: Any 300-level PSL course taken previously or concurrently
PSL201Y1-Y-20219.webTimetableInstructions: Term test will take place Tuesdays from 18:00 to 20:00 (TBA) Toronto time.
PSL201Y1-Y-20219.deliveryInstructions: Lectures will be delivered online. Students will be expected to watch asynchronous lecture videos prior to class meetings; learning is self-paced and not reliant on a meeting schedule. Term tests will be timed and will take place Tuesdays from 18:00 to 20:00 (Toronto time) on scheduled dates (TBA). Lectures 2h/week and optional synchronous help sessions 1h/week (these will be recorded).

PSL280H1-F-20219.courseTitle: Introduction to Physiologic Adaptations of Marine Mammals
PSL280H1-F-20219.courseDescription: Systems approach to physiology of marine mammals in their aquatic environment. Highlights unique features of cardiovascular, respiratory, renal, urinary, and reproductive systems. Introduces relevant physiology, and makes comparisons to human condition and disease.
PSL280H1-F-20219.prerequisite: (BIO120H1, BIO130H1); CHM136H1/CHM138H1/CHM151Y1 or permission of the course coordinator.

PSL299Y1-Y-20219.courseDescription: Credit course for supervised participation in faculty research project. Details at https://www.artsci.utoronto.ca/current/academics/research-opportunities/research-opportunities-program. Not eligible for CR/NCR option.

PSL301H1-S-20219.recommendedPreparation: BIO130H1; CHM136H1/CHM138H1/CHM151Y1; and 1 FCE from any of the following: MAT135H1, MAT136H1, MAT137Y1, MAT157Y1, PHY131H1, PHY132H, PHY151H1, PHY152H1

PSL304H1-F-20219.courseTitle: Topics in Cellular, Molecular and Organismic Physiology I
PSL304H1-F-20219.courseDescription: Control systems, feedback, networks, and both neonatal and adult cardiovascular and respiratory control are the topics examined in detail using homeostasis as a unifying theme. Tutorials involve computer simulations, case studies and/or experimental design. This course is designed for students in the Physiology Specialist and Biological Physics Specialist Programs, although permission is granted to students in other programs upon approval by the Department.
PSL304H1-F-20219.webTimetableInstructions: This course may be added on your ACORN account during your enrolment start date. The interim status (INT) will be updated to approved (APP) or refused (REF) in August. If you require additional information please contact Eva Eng at physiology.undergrad@utoronto.ca.

PSL305H1-S-20219.courseTitle: Topics in Cellular, Molecular and Organismic Physiology II
PSL305H1-S-20219.courseDescription: Molecular, cellular and organismic physiology of the central nervous system, gut, pancreas and glucose-sensing tissues; CNS diseases, obesity and diabetes are used as model systems. Tutorials involve computer simulations. This course is designed for students in the Physiology Specialist and Biological Physics Specialist Programs, although permission is granted to students in other programs upon approval by the Department.
PSL305H1-S-20219.webTimetableInstructions: This course may be added on your ACORN account during your enrolment start date. The interim status (INT) will be updated to approved (APP) or refused (REF) in August. If you require additional information please contact Eva Eng at physiology.undergrad@utoronto.ca.

PSL350H1-S-20219.courseDescription: Extend molecular biology concepts to current scientific literature in mammalian physiology. Apply these principles to disease and complex behaviours. Discuss bioethical issues raised by these techniques and their application. Benefit from three weeks in small group seminars lead by research professors focusing on current advances in mammalian molecular biology.

PSL372H1-F-20219.courseDescription: A laboratory course covering selected topics in physiology. An ancillary fee of $50 will be charged for lab materials.
PSL372H1-F-20219.prerequisite: BIO230H1/(BIO240H1, BIO241H1)/BIO255H1, BCH210H1/BCH242Y1, MAT100-series/PHY100-series, PSL300H1, PSL301H
PSL372H1-F-20219.webTimetableInstructions: This course may be added on your ACORN account during your enrolment start date. The interim status (INT) will be updated to approved (APP) or refused (REF) in August. If you require additional information please contact Eva Eng at physiology.undergrad@utoronto.ca.
PSL372H1-F-20219.deliveryInstructions: Weekly lectures will be delivered online on Thursdays from 12:00 - 14:00. Alternating on-line and in-person labs on Fridays for 4h/week @ 9-1 p.m., synchronous help sessions 1h/week.

PSL374H1-S-20219.courseDescription: A problem-based laboratory course focused on the integration and control of organ systems to understand body functions. Enrollment in this course is restricted to students in the Physiology Specialist and Major Programs although permission is granted to students in other programs upon approval by the Department. An ancillary fee of $50 will be charged for lab materials.

PSL399Y1-Y-20219.courseDescription: Credit course for supervised participation in faculty research project. Details at https://www.artsci.utoronto.ca/current/academics/research-opportunities/research-opportunities-program. Not eligible for CR/NCR option.

PSL404H1-F-20219.courseDescription: Regenerative medicine promises to restore body function that has been lost due to disease, damage or age. Students will explore selected molecular, stem cell and tissue engineering developments to better understand how the body normally functions and how cells, tissues, and organs can be repaired or replaced.
PSL404H1-F-20219.webTimetableInstructions: This course may be added on your ACORN account during your enrolment start date. The interim status (INT) will be updated to approved (APP) or refused (REF) in August. If you require additional information please contact Eva Eng at physiology.undergrad@utoronto.ca.

PSL420H1-F-20219.courseDescription: This course provides an in-depth review of the development and function of the male and female reproductive systems. Topics include sex determination and differentiation, steroidogenesis, gametogenesis, hormonal control of the reproductive axis, the female ovulatory cycle, fertilization and implantation, infertility and assisted reproduction approaches.
PSL420H1-F-20219.webTimetableInstructions: This course may be added on your ACORN account during your enrolment start date. The interim status (INT) will be updated to approved (APP) or refused (REF) in August. If you require additional information please contact Eva Eng at physiology.undergrad@utoronto.ca.

PSL421H1-S-20219.courseTitle: Pregnancy and Birth: From Implantation to Newborn Life
PSL421H1-S-20219.courseDescription: General overview of the integrated physiological events associated with fetal development, pregnancy and birth. The approach emphasizes physiological processes using insights gained from studies of humans, animals, cells and genes. Where appropriate the clinical consequences of aberrant development are reviewed.

PSL425H1-F-20219.courseTitle: Integrative Metabolism and its Endocrine Regulation
PSL425H1-F-20219.courseDescription: This course integrates the newest findings and experimental approaches from cellular and molecular biology into metabolic function at the tissue, organ and whole body level.

PSL432H1-S-20219.courseDescription: Theoretical treatment of neurophysiology. Mathematical modeling and analysis of neurophysiological systems.
PSL432H1-S-20219.webTimetableInstructions: This course may be added on your ACORN account during your enrolment start date. The interim status (INT) will be updated to approved (APP) or refused (REF) in August. If you require additional information please contact Eva Eng at physiology.undergrad@utoronto.ca.

PSL440Y1-Y-20219.courseDescription: Introduction to systems neuroscience. A review of basic neuroanatomy and physiology followed by in-depth study of selected sensory and motor systems, with an emphasis on clinical applications in the second term. Students with an elementary neuroscience background progress to reading neuroscience literature on their own.

PSL445H1-F-20219.courseDescription: Overview of the fundamentals of cellular and molecular aspects of brain function. Course material is updated yearly to reflect the rapid evolution of ideas in Neuroscience.
PSL445H1-F-20219.prerequisite: PSL300H1, PSL301H1, CJH332H1 or permission of instructor
PSL445H1-F-20219.webTimetableInstructions: This course may be added on your ACORN account during your enrolment start date. The interim status (INT) will be updated to approved (APP) or refused (REF) in August. If you require additional information please contact Eva Eng at physiology.undergrad@utoronto.ca.

PSL446H1-S-20219.courseDescription: Explore topics in neurological disorders and treatments to reinforce and expand your knowledge of cellular and molecular neurophysiology. Course material is updated yearly to reflect the rapid evolution of ideas in this area.
PSL446H1-S-20219.prerequisite: PSL300H1, PSL301H1, CJH332H1 or permission of instructor
PSL446H1-S-20219.webTimetableInstructions: This course may be added on your ACORN account during your enrolment start date. The interim status (INT) will be updated to approved (APP) or refused (REF) in August. If you require additional information please contact Eva Eng at physiology.undergrad@utoronto.ca.

PSL450H1-F-20219.courseTitle: Mechanisms of Neural and Endocrinal Secretion
PSL450H1-F-20219.courseDescription: Exocytosis and other aspects of secretion mainly in neurons and neuroendocrine cells, but also in pancreatic cells. Topics include synapse anatomy and physiology, synaptic plasma membrane and vesicle proteins, membrane fusion, genetic tools, endocrine secretion, plasticity in neurotransmitter release, diseases arising from secretion defects.

PSL452H1-F-20219.courseDescription: Biophysics and molecular biology of ion channels. Topics include equivalent circuits for cells, molecular structure of voltage-gated channels, distribution of channels, relationship between single-channel and whole-cell recording, and regulation of channel function by voltage, phosphorylation, G-proteins and metabolites.
PSL452H1-F-20219.webTimetableInstructions: This course may be added on your ACORN account during your enrolment start date. The interim status (INT) will be updated to approved (APP) or refused (REF) in August. If you require additional information please contact Eva Eng at physiology.undergrad@utoronto.ca.

PSL462H1-S-20219.courseDescription: Heart anatomy and development, ion channels and contractile proteins involved in cardiac and smooth muscle contraction are studied. Emphasis is on regulation of electrical and contractile function of kinases, metabolism, volume and ions.
PSL462H1-S-20219.webTimetableInstructions: This course may be added on your ACORN account during your enrolment start date. The interim status (INT) will be updated to approved (APP) or refused (REF) in August. If you require additional information please contact Eva Eng at physiology.undergrad@utoronto.ca.

PSL470H1-S-20219.courseDescription: Development of the cardiovascular system from conception to adulthood with particular emphasis on maturational changes, age-related differences and developmental problems from cellular/molecular to whole organ/system.

PSL472H1-S-20219.courseDescription: This course covers the physiology underlying sleep and circadian rhythms, and their impact on important physiological processes and health. The integrative nature of the basic physiological processes is emphasized via discussions and clinical presentations. Overall, the aim is to present the full spectrum of integrative physiology from molecules and cells to understanding the sick patient.
PSL472H1-S-20219.webTimetableInstructions: This course may be added on your ACORN account during your enrolment start date. The interim status (INT) will be updated to approved (APP) or refused (REF) in August. If you require additional information please contact Eva Eng at physiology.undergrad@utoronto.ca.

PSL480H1-F-20219.courseDescription: This course compares and contrasts the physiological and anatomical adaptations exhibited by the different species of marine mammals in relationship to humans, with respect to diving.

PSL498Y1-Y-20219.courseDescription: Laboratory research project with reading assignments leading to a final report. By special arrangement with a Physiology staff member after admission to course.
